    <fr:title text="Primality by Löb induction">Primality by Löb induction</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>Define "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is prime" by trial division — dividing only by
<html:em>primes</html:em>: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is prime when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \ge  2]]></fr:tex> and no prime <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p < n]]></fr:tex>
divides it. This is a correct characterization but not a structural
definition: the predicate at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> quantifies over the predicate at
every smaller number.</html:p>
    <html:p>It is, exactly, a guarded definition over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\omega ]]></fr:tex>. The motive at
<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is a <html:em>decided proposition</html:em>; <fr:link href="/foreign/stevenschaefer.net/sss-00FR/" title="Later on families" uri="https://stevenschaefer.net/sss-00FR/" display-uri="https://stevenschaefer.net/sss-00FR/" type="local">later on families</fr:link>
hands the step the decided propositions of all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p < n]]></fr:tex>, and the step
forms
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[P_n = {\mathopen {}\left (n \ge  2\right )\mathclose {}} \wedge 
   \forall  p < n.\; P_p \to  p \nmid  n,]]></fr:tex>
deciding it from the finitely many earlier decisions and decidability
of divisibility.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
